<div id="review_2375520146" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2375520146" />
    <a title="Pamela Shropshire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6535930-pamela-shropshire"><img alt="Pamela Shropshire" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1420326873p2/6535930.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2375520146?book_show_action=true">Apr 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pamela Shropshire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pamela Shropshire" href="/user/show/6535930-pamela-shropshire">Pamela Shropshire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/13038644-borders-of-infinity">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6535930-pamela-shropshire?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6535930-pamela-shropshire?shelf=on-my-kindle">on-my-kindle</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2375520146" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1869816600947975365">This collection of novellas contain my favorite of all the Miles stories, the novella called <i>The Mountains of Mourning.</i> I don’t often cry when I read, but there is a moment in that story when I teared up - and I’ve read it before.<br/><br/>The second novella is <i>Labyrinth,</i> which is set on the anything-goes world known as Jackson’s Whole (the name of that world always makes me giggle). It’s a rollicking, happy-ending story about the serious topic of genetic engineering.<br/><br/>The final novella was of most interest</span>
  <span id="freeText1869816600947975365" style="display:none">This collection of novellas contain my favorite of all the Miles stories, the novella called <i>The Mountains of Mourning.</i> I don’t often cry when I read, but there is a moment in that story when I teared up - and I’ve read it before.<br /><br />The second novella is <i>Labyrinth,</i> which is set on the anything-goes world known as Jackson’s Whole (the name of that world always makes me giggle). It’s a rollicking, happy-ending story about the serious topic of genetic engineering.<br /><br />The final novella was of most interest to me, having just finished reading <i>Brothers in Arms</i>, which takes place very soon after the events related in <i>Borders of Infinity.</i> I’m very glad I read it since there were so many references to it in <i>BiA</i>. <br /><br /><i>Borders of Infinity</i> is very good on several levels: it’s a cracking good Miles adventure on its face, but I believe it’s also a retelling of Dante’s <i>Inferno</i> trilogy. <br /><br />The first sentence is Miles thinking “How could I have died and gone to hell without noticing the transition?” Miles has a guide through the prison camp like Dante has Virgil. The prison camp is a circular dome and there are “circles” with the camp formed by people for either harassment of others or protection from the harassers. At one point, Miles publicly carves a man’s (perceived) transgression onto his back, like the offenders in Dante’s Hell bear physical signs of their sins. <br /><br />There is a woman named Beatrice who at the end leads Miles up the ramp of the shuttle (the ramp has been damaged and Beatrice falls to her death). Miles’s guide, named Suegar, has a page from a book that he calls Scripture, which I’m almost certain is from Bunyan’s <i>The Pilgrim’s Progress.</i><br /><br />There are probably other parallels that I didn’t pick up, but it seems like too many to be coincidence.<br /><br />So, stars? <br /><br /><i>The Mountains of Mourning</i> gets ALL the stars. 5++++<br /><i>Labyrinth</i> gets 3<br /><i>Borders of Infinity</i> gets 5.<br /><br />I’m going to round it up to 5 for the collection.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1869816600947975365" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


