  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_93260531" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/93260531" />
    <a title="Lisa Feld" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3407733-lisa-feld"><img alt="Lisa Feld" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442510135p2/3407733.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/93260531?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisa Feld" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisa Feld" href="/user/show/3407733-lisa-feld">Lisa Feld</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780671578299" href="/book/show/76811.Borders_of_Infinity">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3407733-lisa-feld?shelf=bard">bard</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer93260531" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8543323771212296813">Even though the novellas in this collection have been worked into the omnibus editions, I still keep and reread this collection because I love the device Bujold uses to thread them together here: hopped up on drugs and recovering from surgery, Miles is being interrogated about his past missions to clear himself and his father of charges of embezzlement (because a covert mercenary fleet doesn’t fit easily into an imperial military budget). By reflecting on the events in the novellas, Miles comes </span>
  <span id="freeText8543323771212296813" style="display:none">Even though the novellas in this collection have been worked into the omnibus editions, I still keep and reread this collection because I love the device Bujold uses to thread them together here: hopped up on drugs and recovering from surgery, Miles is being interrogated about his past missions to clear himself and his father of charges of embezzlement (because a covert mercenary fleet doesn’t fit easily into an imperial military budget). By reflecting on the events in the novellas, Miles comes to some interesting realizations about their impact on his life. <br /><br />“Mountains of Mourning” is a murder mystery set in the backwoods of Barrayar. For me, this story is the crux of the whole Vorkosigan Saga: people who invest everything in a technology, ideology, career, or relationship and then have to figure out how to start over when everything they valued becomes obsolete. <br /><br />“Labyrinth” introduces us to a number of players on Jackson’s Whole who will become essential in later books, and I love how Bel and Taura interact with Miles. <br /><br />“Borders of Infinity” is a bit of a slow burn, but any time I get to see Miles scrambling to come out on top of a situation with literally nothing at his disposal, I’m entertained.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8543323771212296813" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

